The Financial Street "cold" behind, is an invisible "war epidemic" , and will be a protracted war. Because the economic and financial impact of the epidemic has not yet been fully shown, even if the epidemic is over, back to the economy itself, the financial challenges still

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Photograph by Lai lap

By Zhang Wei, Yingxin, Yu Yan, Wayne Wang

Editor | Yuen Man

February 10,2020, new pneumonia epidemic, Beijing ushered in the resumption of Business Day.

North of Chang 'an street in Fuxingmen, the financial street was so quiet with long lines of cars and people that it was deserted until 6 pm. A financial regulator told Caijing that the scene has been going on for several days because he has been working overtime for more than 10 days since the third day of the first lunar month (January 27) , and it is cold to see the street every day.

According to the notice of the State Council General Office on the extension of the 2020 Spring Festival holiday, all types of financial institutions and financial infrastructure related institutions will start their normal work on February 3,2020.

Indeed, on that quiet financial street, many financiers had been on the job as early as January 27, handling holiday financial services and researching post-stability day financial market proposals. However, affected by the epidemic, some people choose to work from home, the implementation of rotating duty, and the receipt of documents, the need for intranet only to the unit.

The financial regulator is one of the latter and has no choice. He said a sudden outbreak of new pneumonia had broken the rhythm of the financial system.

On February 9, Liu Guoqiang, deputy governor of the People's Bank of China, said that under the guidance of the Finance Committee of the State Council, the People's Bank of China will make winning the fight against epidemic prevention and control a top priority in its current financial work, and will promptly introduce a series of policies and measures, do a good job in financial support of epidemic prevention and control. One Line two meetings for the "war epidemic" one after another and issued a number of policies.

The financial support for epidemic prevention and control is mainly reflected in two aspects: First, supporting enterprises that produce medical goods and necessities during the Spring Festival to work overtime; and second, helping small and medium-sized micro enterprises and private enterprises to fight against the epidemic and tide over the difficulties, restore production in an orderly manner and promote the healthy operation of the economic system.

On February 10, the central bank set up a special reloan of 300 billion yuan, and the first batch of funds was officially released, which means that, some enterprises that produce important medical supplies such as protective clothing and face masks for use in response to the epidemic will be able to obtain loan funds within a day or two at the earliest, and their actual financing cost will be less than 1.6 per cent thanks to the discount policy.

Wang Tao, chief China economist at UBS securities, told Caijing that in the face of the epidemic, the financial system has a very important role to play in ensuring the stable operation of the economy and financial markets, of which abundant liquidity is the most important.

Financial Street "cold" behind, is an invisible "war epidemic.

On Feb. 3, the central bank provided 1.2 trillion yuan of liquidity to the market immediately after the opening of the market after the holiday and simultaneously lowered interest rates. Before the operation, the stock market and the foreign exchange market were once under pressure due to panic.

The next day, panic abated and financial markets gradually returned to normal.

The financial sectors, led by the Central Bank, responded to the epidemic by providing liquidity, stabilizing market expectations and ensuring liquidity in capital markets and the functioning of the economy, Wang said. In this respect, it should be said that the response of the financial system has been good and has withstood the test.

Zhong Nanshan told reporters on Feb. 11 that the peak number of new cases of pneumonia in COVID-19 is expected to occur in mid to late February and may end by April.

"I hope the epidemic will pass as soon as possible! " The regulator told Caijing, adding that they still have a lot of work to do after the epidemic, and that supporting enterprises to resume work and preventing inflation are follow-up issues.

Evergrande Research Institute recently analysis that the epidemic will interrupt China's economic weak stability at the end of 2019, in the context of greater downward pressure on the economy, breaking 6 is a probability event, may break 5 in the first quarter. In addition, the financial sector in the follow-up to the rise in non-performing rate, securities trading volume decline.

Clearly, the financial industry faces a protracted battle.

One financial practitioner said that this persistence is reflected not only in the measures taken by financial institutions to assist the spread of the epidemic, but also in how people deal with the economic and financial impact of the epidemic after it is over, protecting the economy and maintaining financial health.

At the press conference of the State New Administration of China on February 15, Fan Yifei, deputy governor of the People's Bank of China, stressed that at present, the prevention and control of the epidemic has reached the most critical stage, and the People's Bank will implement 30 measures of financial support for the prevention and control of the epidemic, we will support enterprises that are in a position to do so to resume work and production as soon as possible, to keep the economy running smoothly, to minimize the impact of the epidemic, and to strive to achieve the goals and tasks set by the Party Central Committee.

Pamper the market: Panic dissipates

"More than 3,000 shares in the two markets have fallen by their daily limit, the onshore and offshore Renminbi have broken the '7' mark, and the DR007[ seven-day repo rate in the interbank market ] was once up about 30bp-40bp... "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On the first day of trading, the financial markets were rattled by the COVID-19 epidemic.

Beyond the numbers, there is panic. Under the influence of the continued build-up of risk aversion before the holiday, some banks have doubled the amount of reserves that commercial banks have set aside to protect depositors'interests, meet deposit payments and ensure liquidity, the move saw a rare net inflow of money from banks on the first day of trading, changing their status.

How did this happen? Jie Liu, the Balance Sheet Management Department of Everbright Bank, told Caijing that the interest rate on funds rose sharply at the time, first because the large payment system was delayed and the funds put in by the Central Bank before the holiday were facing a concentrated maturity from February 3 to 5, second, the outbreak of the epidemic makes the market preventive capital demand and risk aversion increased. "If there is no outbreak this year and the Chinese New Year holiday is not extended, as has been the case in the past, liquidity will be very abundant in February as cash gradually returns. "

Because of the epidemic, and because of the extension of holidays, some bank deposits due before the festival can not be renewed, leading to a sharp decline in general deposits, putting pressure on bank liquidity management, the banks have since replenished their funds by issuing cds (certificates of deposit) and applying to the central bank for Omo (reverse repurchase operations) . In addition, before the opening, the Hang Seng Index, the asia-pacific stock index has fallen sharply, also constitutes the bank to avoid the risk sentiment nervous reason.

The panic was evident on the Stock Exchange, where the GC001 repo rate rose as much as 100 BP in the morning and GC007 was up more than 70 BP, Jie Liu recalled. In general, Jie Liu said, when the interbank market becomes tight, some non financial institutions turn to the exchange market for funding, which in turn increases the degree of tightness in the exchange market.

To the surprise of many investors, the scare was short-lived.

On the opening day, the central bank put 1.2 trillion yuan of liquidity into the market, while protecting investors, "the market was hit by the fall, does not affect the long-term trend, investors should not panic. ". Subsequently, the funds rate began to fall gradually. The Shanghai Composite Index rose for the next seven sessions, while the chinext index rose 8.17 per cent in eight sessions, its highest level in three years.

The yield on the 10-year note closed at 2.80 per cent in the first week of trading, down 22.6 BP from the previous week, and the dollar's median value against the Renminbi was 6.97, down from its December average of 7.01. Money markets responded more amicably to central bank liquidity, with the DR007 average closing at 2.33 per cent, down 25.14 BP from last week's average.

In addition to the Central Bank's efforts to shore up liquidity in financial markets, Jie Liu said, there are two other reasons for the reasonable abundance of funds: First, with companies returning to work, cash is flowing back into the banking system, and second, the subsequent decline in the demand of financial institutions for risk aversion, inter-bank market traditional large banks to increase the size of the financial sector.

In the view of a financial regulator, the financial market panic caused by the epidemic quickly dissipated, indicating that China's financial regulation and financial market participants more mature. "The central bank controls and controls liquidity at a much higher level than before, including window guidance and timely voice. ".

Jie Liu agrees. Taking the money market and the stock market as an example, he said that in general, when the price of funds is high, it is a good opportunity for the banks that have raised funds to make profits. However, on the day of the opening of the market, due to increased demand for safe haven, the bank capital business turns to the defensive mode, and tends to reserve the precautionary fund to maintain the stability of the bank's Day liquidity, in order to deal with the market uncertainty.

In addition, during the a-share market suspension, the international market reacted to the epidemic with a more intense reaction. The overall stock market in the asia-pacific region was weak. The domestic market generally predicted a sharp drop on the first day of opening, but the country continued to open as normal, this stems from our country many years system consummation as well as the opening to the outside world dynamics increases the support comes from the self-confidence. "under the restriction of the relevant policies, the speculativeness of the micro-subject participants is weakened, and more attention is paid to the fundamental aspects and value judgment of the Holding Company. ".

Pan Gongsheng, deputy governor of the People's Bank of China, said at a press conference at the Guoxin Office on February 7 that the financial markets are very sensitive and can price risks quickly. After short-term fluctuations in the stock market and foreign exchange market at the beginning of the market opening, are Almost back to normal. "The regular opening of China's financial markets, especially the stock market and the foreign exchange market, on February 3, as scheduled, shows the determination of the Chinese government to firmly uphold market rules and also shows that China's financial markets are maturing. ".

UBS expects the DR007 to stay low in the first quarter, with an average of about 2.4 per cent, adjusted by the Central Bank. They also expect the Central Bank to conduct a sizeable medium-term lending facility (MLF) operation to guide the loan market quote rate (LPR) on February 20.

"In general, liquidity has to operate on the basis of economic activity, which stops if the economy is inactive. The subsequent gradual recovery in economic activity can also lead to an effective functioning of liquidity,"Jie Liu said. Under the influence of the epidemic, the pressure of stable growth remains high, and the monetary policy of the Central Bank is expected to continue to play a counter-cyclical regulatory role. When the subsequent Omo expires, the Central Bank can not rule out the possibility of adopting new MLF as a hedge and cutting MLF interest rates by 10 BP, the reasonable abundance of liquidity in the future market is optimistic.

For Financial Markets, Jie Liu believes the impact of the outbreak on domestic financial market volatility is short term and relatively limited in the medium to long term. For the Stock Market, the valuation of A-shares is currently at a low level in the past five years, which is highly attractive. With the increase in the degree of opening up to the outside world, the medium-and long-term positive trend of the a-shares market has not changed. For the bond market, after this round of adjustment, the Bond Market Valuation has basically reflected the market's expectation of the epidemic situation and the future economic fundamentals. There is limited room for further strength. If there is a compensatory rebound in the future, the bond market will face some adjustment pressure, considering that the interest rate differential between China and the United States remains high, the RMB is in a strong state after the agreement of trade friction between China and the United States, and the pressure of RMB depreciation caused by the outbreak is generally limited.

Fighting the epidemic: services are never interrupted

On the first day after the Lunar New Year holiday (January 25) , the People's Bank of China raised the limit for a single payment from 1 million yuan to 500 million yuan for a 7-to-24-hour continuous micro-payment system. At the same time, from January 25 to January 30, the operating limit of the small payment system will be relaxed to ensure the timely processing of the transfer of large funds.

Fan Yifei disclosed that from January 24 to February 14, the central bank's large and small payment systems handled 393,500 payments of more than 10 million yuan, with a total amount of 77.37 trillion yuan. Of this total, 872 transactions involving 44.796 billion yuan were related to the fight against the epidemic.

According to a person close to the payment and settlement system told Caijing, it doesn't take long to adjust the payment amount, and the staff on duty need to be on duty 24 hours in order to be able to implement the policy in the first place, but during an outbreak, to avoid being affected by an outbreak, a person on duty would have to be on duty for seven to 24 hours at a time, as in the past, is replaced once a day.

At the other end of the bank card call center, before the Spring Festival, realized the severity of the epidemic, and has already booked the plan to go home staff communication and consultation, realized the majority of Staff Refund to stay on duty. "The call center works seven to 24 hours a day, and the staff did not go home. On the one hand, they avoided the risk of being infected by the epidemic, and on the other hand, they made sure that their business would not be affected during the epidemic. " The head of the call center said that for those affected by the epidemic, people who can't pay their credit cards on time have a longer tolerance period.

The regulator said financial services had never been disrupted during the Lunar New Year holiday. "As in many service industries, many of the dangerous jobs of bank branches and money handlers continued during the outbreak. "

Fan Yifei said that after the outbreak of the epidemic, the People's Bank of China (PBOC) promptly initiated emergency response plans to strengthen the important infrastructure of the financial system, as well as the operation and maintenance of key positions and the continuous emergency duty, the financial sector's technical support capacity and emergency response mechanism have withstood the test.

Financial markets function like a lubricant in the economic system, helping to keep the economy running smoothly, Wang said. The financial system, like systems like electricity or transportation, is an infrastructure of the economy. When an outbreak occurs, the financial system can not have a sudden shortage of liquidity, credit crunch situation.

Beyond basic services, it is also critical that financial support policies fall into place.

With 300 billion yuan of special central bank loans gradually landed, the market is more concerned about getting "emergency money" enterprises will misappropriate funds? Shevin, the governor of the Guangdong Branch of the Agricultural Development Bank of China ("Agricultural Development Bank") , told Caijing that the current batch of special re-loans is mainly provided to key enterprises in the prevention and control of the epidemic, some companies have long-term business dealings with the bank, while others have never had dealings with it. For the former, because between the bank and the enterprise comparison understanding, the main consideration repayment source, cash flow and other factors. For businesses that have never dealt with them before, it is mainly through "closed management" that funds are "put to good use" .

"'closed management' means we ask companies to provide proof of purchase contracts and so on, and then we make payments directly to the upstream companies, emphasizing 'fiduciary payments' and reducing 'discretionary payments' , " Shevin said.

"CAIJING" reporter noted that although private banks can not apply for special re-loans within the scope of the bank, but it also used in the loan closed-end management methods. Xinwang Bank President Zhao Weixing revealed that after the outbreak, Xinwang Bank mainly increased investment in enterprises related to the fight against the epidemic. If the enterprise applies for funds exceeding 250,000 yuan, the bank will pay the funds directly to the upstream supplier.

As of 12 noon on February 14, the amount of credit support provided by banking financial institutions to combat the epidemic exceeded 537 billion yuan, said Liang Tao, vice chairman of the China Banking Regulatory Commission, at a press conference held by the Guoxin Administration.

In view of the production and investment of enterprises in the epidemic area are greatly affected and liquidity is difficult, the effect of CSRC opening the "Green Channel" of financing is beginning to appear gradually. So far, four Wuhan companies have issued bonds through the "Green Channel" , to raise 2.8 billion yuan; there are 10 epidemic prevention and Control Company bonds and one ABS issued, a total of 11.23 billion yuan, several anti-epidemic special bonds are planning to be issued. Equity and venture capital funds in the anti-epidemic category has been 46 projects, the amount of 17.046 billion yuan.

However, under the tide of active participation in the fight against the epidemic, there are also some discordant voices. In the panic of the epidemic, some insurance salesmen have taken advantage of the situation to engage in viral marketing, with emotional posts about how pathetic it is to be infected without commercial insurance.

On the first day of construction on February 3, the personal insurance department, Property Insurance Department and Intermediary Department of the CBRC issued a notice at the same time, requiring insurance companies to do a good job in related business areas. Among them, the document requirements of the Personal Insurance Department, strictly prohibit the use of the epidemic situation to hype up insurance products, strictly prohibit the use of the epidemic situation to induce customers to retire old to buy new, strictly prohibit the development and design of the COVID-19 proprietary products that lack pricing basis, it is strictly prohibited to advertise the extended liability of insurance products as COVID-19 products.

Because there is no specific medicine for NCP, and in view of the characteristics of the disease, such as the difficulty in diagnosing the disease at the initial stage, the hidden condition and the long course of the disease, in order to alleviate the economic pressure on the insured customers and families, the CBRC, based on the people-oriented principle, insurance companies will be allowed to extend their insurance coverage to cover new cases of pneumonia, to eliminate waiting periods, deductibles and restrictions on designated hospitals, and to simplify claims processing.

It is worth noting that there are still some gaps in financial support.

With the spread of the epidemic, such as catering, tourism, film, transportation, education and training, and other industries suffered a lot, in which business owners, self-employed households were inevitably affected. A number of small and medium-sized enterprises have told the "finance and economics" reporter, the current biggest problem is due to forced closure of the current shortage of funds, if the problem is difficult to solve, it is difficult to "winter.

Shevin said bluntly that from a policy bank perspective, the epidemic reflects China's urban and rural infrastructure in the construction of some weak links. Therefore, in the future, the bank will further strengthen its support to the improvement of rural human settlements and the construction of urban and rural public health facilities. At the same time, after this outbreak, will also consider in the epidemic prevention and control of material reserves and other aspects.

"The role of banks is to work with the real economy, and I have always been opposed to putting finance first. It would not be a healthy society to blindly chase some financial gain. Banks should first look at national policies or the Development Direction of the real industry, what they are doing, and then we will quickly provide funds and provide financial services in such a way that they can co-operate and help, instead of being led by finance,"Zhao said bluntly, "I am particularly concerned that companies end up giving up their physical interests for financial gain. "

Economic pressure: Broad Credit Support

Market analysts generally agree that the COVID-19 outbreak put a lot of pressure on China's economy in the first quarter. UBS China economists expect GDP growth to slow to 3.8% year on year in the first quarter of 2020 and to slow to 5.4% for the full year.

Recently, UBS macro once again said that if GDP in the first quarter fell at an annualised rate of 3 per cent from the previous quarter and exceeded our benchmark forecast of a 1.5 per cent decline (down to 3.4 per cent year-on-year growth and below the current benchmark forecast of 3.8 per cent) , even if economic activity rebounds sharply in the second and fourth quarters, GDP growth is likely to slow to about 5 per cent in 2020.

Wang Tao told Caijing that the biggest problem facing the economy is the negative impact caused by the new pneumonia outbreak, so the most important policy now is to control the epidemic and prevent the economy from suffering too much negative impact. If the epidemic continues to develop, staff can not go to work, enterprises can not resume production, the negative impact on the economy will be expanded.

A macro-analyst told Caijing that the epidemic was very different from SARS, and the number of infections was unprecedented, as was the control that led to the closure of Hubei, nationwide isolation and delayed resumption of work. These measures are good for dealing with the epidemic, but they also put the economy "dormant" as never before, cutting off cash flow for companies. With so many "unprecedented" combinations, it is not so much SARS as the financial crisis of 2008. In the face of this unprecedented series of circumstances, it is easy to expect instability, it is easy to let this round of "weak stability" by the "Black Swan" interrupted. Weak economic indicators continue to catalyze pessimistic expectations, which tend to resonate with economic weakness and reinforce each other, leading to a vicious circle.

In this more pessimistic view, financial work is seen as a key element in stabilizing expectations. The analyst pointed out that the first thing to do was to stabilize expectations in order to stabilize growth. In particular, the first two months of the economic fundamentals are not released, is a data vacuum, all parties are in the Information asymmetry, only reference to financial market data, to guide expectations.

Financial Management Work is crucial, a financial researcher told the "finance and economics" reporter, first, to maintain adequate liquidity, loosen the credit line, promote enterprises to restore investment willingness, consumers to restore consumption willingness; Second, we will open up the financial sector and create new ones. We will draw on the mature experience of international financial markets to make our domestic financial markets more rational and our liquidity more beneficial to all types of enterprises.

The above-mentioned financial regulators told Caijing that ensuring the supply of medical necessities, supporting large-scale enterprises to resume production and preventing inflation are all important tasks for financial services. "In addition to the shortage of medical supplies for epidemic prevention and control, People's Daily necessities will soon be in short supply and out of supply. If prices rise, society will be thrown into a more serious panic, " he said, finance needs to continue to think about this.

Even if the epidemic ends and the economy returns to itself, finance will still be tested.

At the beginning of this year, with the risk of stagflation in the economy and the conflict between "stable growth" and "inflation control" as the two ultimate objectives of monetary policy, the decision-making became more difficult, the primary objective of monetary policy of China's central bank has been tilted toward stable growth.

The People's Bank of China put forward in the "2020 working conference of the People's Bank of China" that we should keep the prudent monetary policy flexible and moderate. We will strengthen counter-cyclical regulation, maintain reasonable and ample liquidity, and promote the growth of monetary credit and social financing commensurate with economic development.

Huatai Macro Li Chao team has proposed that the "adapt" to the core refers to when the economic growth rate under pressure, the Central Bank may increase the scale of credit cooperatives by pre-fine-tuning to stabilize economic growth, that is, the essential requirement is to expand credit.

Pan Gongsheng pointed out that the central bank in a serious analysis and assessment of the impact of the epidemic on China's economy, a good policy reserve. The next step is to increase the intensity of counter-cyclical adjustment, maintain reasonable and ample liquidity, and provide a good monetary and financial environment for the real economy. The second is to further deepen the reform of interest rate marketization and improve the transmission mechanism of market quoted interest rates, we need to improve the transmission effect of monetary policy and reduce the cost of social financing. Third, we need to continue to give full play to the role of structural monetary policy tools, such as targeted reductions in interest rates, refinancing loans and rediscounting, we will increase support for key areas and weak links in the national economy.

Shen Jianguang, chief economist at jd.com, told Caijing earlier this year that the central bank's biggest concern and challenge for monetary policy in 2020 is how to improve its effectiveness.

Affected by the outbreak, many research institutions expect the Central Bank of China to introduce more cut in 2020 and interest rate cut measures. Zhang Ming, chief economist at Ping an securities, raised his forecast for central bank rate cuts to three or four times from two or three, and said China's central bank would cut interest rates more sharply in 2020 at the level of SLF-MLF-LPR.

However, the momentum of monetary policy is still limited by the speed of CPI growth. In December 2019, China's CPI and PPI were 4.5% and-0.5% respectively. Analysts believe that the new pneumonia epidemic may lead to CPI year-on-year increase for longer, or a slower rate of decline. With this in mind, the dominant market view is that monetary easing in 2020 is likely to occur more in the second half of the year.

On the question of inflation, Fan Yifei said in response to a reporter's question that now, as the resumption of work and production still needs a process, whether on the demand side or other aspects have brought certain pressure to price stability. However, to maintain a prudent monetary policy, this premise has not changed, in view of these issues we will take timely measures to adjust, I believe that China will never have a large-scale inflation.

Next, what can the financial system do to support economic growth?

Wang Tao judges that the Central Bank will also cut reserve requirements and interest rates, and that the China Banking Regulatory Commission will temporarily relax some regulatory policies, such as postponing debt repayment deadlines and continuing to increase credit support for small and medium-sized enterprises. Given the pressures on the real economy at the moment, "It is necessary to delay the due dates of debts when companies are in difficulty" . Banks can't take out loans. At the same time, the subsequent steady growth also needs the further support of the credit.

For now, regulators are expected to extend the transition period for the new rules. Pan Gongsheng said at the press conference that the People's Bank of China is working with the China Banking Regulatory Commission to make some technical assessments, and it is possible to extend the transition period of the new regulation.

On how to define the safe bottom line for the central bank to increase liquidity, Wang Tao believes that the central bank will have comprehensive considerations, and can refer to changes in market interest rates to weigh the needs of the economy, and will not indulge in unrestrained water.

The macro analysts said infrastructure investment was the fastest-yielding demand tool to offset the impact on GDP growth in the first quarter. He said that the poor performance of infrastructure construction in 2019 was due to the heavy debt burden and strict control brought about by traditional credit and bond financing channels, as well as restrictions on trust and other channels under the new capital management regulations, and the failure to connect new financial instruments and financing channels.

Moreover, there is debate about whether infrastructure alone will stabilise the economy, or whether real estate will drive it. The Central Bank issued the "third quarter 2019 monetary policy implementation report, " said, "in accordance with the basic principle of 'city policy' , the implementation of a long-term real estate management mechanism, real estate as a short-term means of stimulating the economy. "

Previous analysis suggested that "housing is not speculation" does not mean that the real estate financial policy continued to tighten, that housing-related financing has been reduced to a reasonable and conventional level, suggesting that the future will not continue to reduce the proportion of housing-related financing, this also deserves attention.

Sheng Songcheng, former head of the central bank's Adjustment Department and a counselor at the Shanghai Municipal People's Government and a professor at China Europe International Business School, said that inaction on stimulus measures should not be equated with continued tightening of policy. At present, the real estate industry still plays an important role in China's economy. Under the background of the downward pressure on the economy and the gradual formation of the turning point of the real estate industry, the real estate regulation and control should no longer be tightened substantially, it is more appropriate to keep the overall regulation and control stable at the current level.

The data showed that the balance of broad money (M2) was 198.65 trillion yuan at the end of December 2019, up 8.7 percent year-on-year, with growth rates 0.5 percentage points higher than the end of last month and 0.6 percentage points higher than the same period last year. The cumulative increase in the scale of social financing in 2019 was 25.58 trillion yuan, 3.08 trillion yuan more than the previous year.

Given the pressure to prevent and control systemic financial risks, the Chinese government will not overreact to the negative impact of the new pneumonia outbreak, Zhang said. For example, deleveraging, risk management and strong regulation of financial institutions will not be fundamentally relaxed. For example, the regulation of the real estate industry (especially the first and second-line key cities) will not be a major reversal. Again, macro-policy will not repeat the "flood irrigation. ".

Financial risk: The battle for assets

Although finance is considered to be a secondary issue of the economy, the risks inherent in the financial system can not be ignored, given the lagging performance of finance, from serving the epidemic of the war of resistance to stable economic growth.

Evergrande research has previously pointed out that during 2003 SARS, transportation, accommodation, catering, financial and other service sectors were hit hard, the second quarter GDP sub-categories were down 5.4,3.6 and 3.6 percentage points from the first quarter respectively.

Wang Tao believes that the analysis of the financial sector's contribution to GDP is not significant, because finance itself has a lot of added value, can work from home, continue to lend. The financial sector was less directly hit by the outbreak than other services.

However, the financial system will also be affected by the negative impact of the epidemic. Wang Tao believes that the epidemic will impact the economy. Many enterprises will not be able to return to work for the time being, lack of cash flow, and their revenues will drop. Serious enterprises will even go bankrupt and close down. Default and bad debt rates will definitely rise, the quality of bank assets will be affected to a certain extent. Coupled with the need for increased credit support for stable growth, the outbreak will increase the potential risks to the financial system.

The negative impact of the outbreak on the financial sector has already been felt. Zhao weixing felt deeply about this. He told CAIJING that in the first quarter, the number of applications for personal credit business declined by nearly 30 percent compared with the same period last year. On the other hand, the number of users who applied for deferment of loan repayment before the epidemic was around 40, and it is now increasing sharply every day, hundreds of late-payment applications in a single day. If the outbreak continues, the numbers will continue to climb. The most direct impact on the banks is the rate of return to decline, which in turn leads to a reduction in the amount of effective capital investment. As a result, liquidity pressures on banks have soared.

A number of small and medium-sized banks also told the "finance and economics" reporter that many enterprises now want to solve the funding problem by lengthening the account period, the subsequent will increase the bank's liquidity pressure. After all, banks are not "blood-makers" ; they are merely a link in the flow.

In view of the low proportion of direct financing in the scale of social financing and the high proportion of indirect financing, the quality of banking assets is considered as the risk concern.

Fitch Ratings also said that while China's banks had less than 4 percent exposure to deposits and loans in Hubei Province, where the new pneumonia outbreak is occurring, but if the rapid spread of the disease and the control measures taken by the relevant authorities cause large-scale business in other parts of China, the quality of bank assets will be under great pressure.

There are also concerns among banks involved in special refinancing. "special refinancing emphasizes 'EMErgency' . If the bank follows the original procedures, it will be difficult to do so in a timely manner, but this is actually in conflict with the prudent principles of the bank, and what should be done if we have a large number of bad debts after that, " said the head of the credit business of a major state-owned bank, if banks overthink their risks, they will surely demand more from companies, which will have less access to capital. It is hard for banks to strike a balance, and they end up having to lower the "Bar" At particular times.

Shevin also admitted to the "CAIJING" reporter, in order to ensure that "life-saving money" in place, there will be reduced some of the original procedures, relax the "threshold" of the situation. For example, before the credit line is mainly through the bank's own system to measure given, but now is the actual needs of enterprises to consider a little more.

How do you minimize risk? Even if the standards were relaxed, Shevin stressed, there would be two bottom lines: a clear sense of where the money is going and a sense that the risks are manageable.

The stress on asset quality was the topic of conversation among most banking respondents. The head of a policy-oriented bank said bluntly that according to the current national policy, enterprises related to epidemic prevention are encouraged to produce, and the government will purchase and store the bulk of the production, while the government will certainly do so through local finance or some state-owned enterprises, if this degree is not well handled, it may lead to new hidden debts of local governments, which will have an impact on the asset quality of policy banks.

Among them, small and medium-sized banks are potentially under greater pressure, "The continuous production cuts and work stoppages have made it difficult for many small and medium-sized enterprises to sustain themselves. The impact on some local commercial banks, rural credit cooperatives and village and township banks, which mainly invest in small and medium-sized enterprises, will be relatively large. It may directly lead to a sharp drop in their profits and a sharp rise in the non-performing rate that year, " the general manager of a city commercial bank in southern China told Caijing.

Even if some large joint-stock banks have more abundant capital, but face a shortage of desirable assets. "banks will be required to increase their lending to the relevant sectors affected by the outbreak, and there will be relatively large pricing concessions, which will actually have an impact on the quality of our assets, " said a person with a joint-stock bank, but Banks'deposit costs are still high, which has an impact on profitability and capital replenishment and is expected to lower the benchmark deposit rate.

However, given the one-off temporary impact of the epidemic, Wang Tao believes that the systemic risks of our financial system are manageable.

According to the CBRC, the balance of non-performing loans of commercial banks was 2.37 trillion yuan at the end of the third quarter of 2019, up 132 billion yuan from the end of the previous quarter; the non-performing loan ratio of commercial banks was 1.86 percent, up 0.05 percentage point from the end of the previous quarter.

"The reserve coverage of banks has reached more than 180 percent, and there are sufficient resources to cope with the increase in bad loans, " Zhou Liang, vice chairman of the China Banking Regulatory Commission, said at a State Council news conference.

Still, the banks have their own claims. The head of a National Bank branch told Caijing that he hoped the regulator would be more tolerant of loan conditions, procedures (the reasonableness of the implementation) and non-performing loans. Some banks also called for anti-epidemic measures, such as lowering loan interest rates and increasing credit lines, to be taken into account by the central bank when assessing the MPA (macro-prudential assessment system) .

"Financial Stability" is one of the central bank's hidden goals, according to Huatai Macro Li Chao's team, although in early 2018 the central bank proposed establishing the twin pillars of monetary policy and macro prudence, since then, the goal of "financial stability" has been partially separated from the ultimate goal of the Central Bank, which is dominated by macro-prudential policy.

Hao Zhiyun, a senior risk manager at Industrial and Commercial Bank of China, told CAIJING: On the one hand, the regulatory authorities should strengthen financial supervision and maintain financial stability. It is necessary to assess the risks of the financial stability system, provide liquidity to the market in a timely manner, try to stabilize capital market expectations, Guide Credit Fund services to support the real economy, and tighten local financial regulatory responsibilities in key areas of the epidemic. On the other hand, financial institutions should strengthen risk management and timely disposal of bad. Risk early warning, stress test and compliance inspection should be used to prevent, deal with and resolve the risk brought by the epidemic. In particular, small and medium-sized financial institutions, to expand the capital of the supplementary channels, targeted services private, micro and Pratt & Whitney.

(interns Wang Yuting and Zhang Linyi contributed to this report)
